Mortality of doctors in Taiwan.

Shang TF(1), Chen PC, Wang JD.

Author information:
(1)Bureau of International Cooperation, Department of Health, Executive Yuan, 36 
Tacheng Street, Taipei City 103, Taiwan.

BACKGROUND: Working in clinical practice involves exposure to many hazards, 
resulting in ongoing concerns regarding mortality in doctors when compared with 
the general public.
AIMS: To evaluate the survival data of all Taiwanese doctors and to ascertain 
whether doctors experience premature mortality.
METHODS: Death and census data from 1990 to 2006 were obtained for all 
practising doctors in Taiwan. Cause-specific standardized mortality ratios 
(SMRs) were calculated via the Life Table Analysis System using the general 
population of Taiwan as the reference.
RESULTS: All the SMRs of different medical specialties were below 0.34. Doctors 
in Taiwan were found to be less likely to die from all causes, including suicide 
and drug abuse. The SMRs for suicide and drug abuse were generally below 0.50 
[SMR = 0.14, 95% confidence interval (CI) 0.09-0.21 and SMR = 0.16, 95% CI 
0.07-0.32, respectively].
CONCLUSIONS: The risks of all-cause and cause-specific mortality of doctors were 
found to be lower than those of the general population in Taiwan.

